e found for \(\hat{c}_{4}\) in equation (23.18) . 23.7 Adjusted \(R^{2}\) In section 21.9 we introduced the measure \(R^{2}\), which measures what proportion of the variation in the explained variable, for example \(y\), that can be explained by the variation in the explanatory variable, for example \(x\): \[  egin{equation} R^{2}=1- rac{\sum\left(y_{i}-\hat{y_{i}}ight)^{2}}{\sum\left(y_{i}- ar{y}ight)^{2}} \end{equation} \] where \(y_{i}-\hat{y}\) indicates the difference between observed \(y_{i}\) and predicted \(\hat{y}_{i}\). The expression \(y_{i}- ar{y}\) indicates the difference between observed \(y_{i}\) and the mean \( ar{y}\). Say now that we have a regression model with k number of explanatory variables: \[  egin{equation} y=b_{0}+b_{1}x_{1}+b_{2}x_{2}+...+b_{k}x_{k}+e 	ag{23.23} \end{equation} \] where all \(b\) are constant coefficients and all \(x\) are explanatory variables. Coefficients and variables are numbered to mark that they differ from each other. The term \(e\) is the error term. Let us rewrite the calculation of \(R^{2}\) by reminding ourselves of how \(\hat{y}\) is defined from the regression model: \[  egin{align} R^{2} &amp; =1- rac{\sum\left(y_{i}-\hat{y_{i}}ight)^{2}}{\sum\left(y_{i}- ar{y}ight)^{2}}\ &amp; =1- rac{\sum\left(y_{i}-\left(\hat{b}_{0}+\hat{b}_{1}x_{1}+...+\hat{b}_{k}x_{k}+\hat{e}_{i}ight)ight)^{2}}{\sum\left(y_{i}- ar{y}ight)^{2}}
onumber \end{align} \] where \(i\) marks the number of the observation. Now we will add to our regression model in equation (23.23) another explanatory variable: \(x_{k+1}\) and its slope coefficient \(b_{k+1}\). The new regression model will have \(k+1\) number of explanatory variables. \(R^{2}\) for this new model becomes: \[  egin{equation} 	ext{R^{2}}=1- rac{\sum\left(y_{i}-\left(\hat{b}_{0}+\hat{b}_{1}x_{1}+...+\hat{b}_{k}x_{k}+\hat{b}_{k+1}x_{k+1}+\hat{e}_{i}ight)ight)^{2}}{\sum\left(y_{i}- ar{y}ight)^{2}} \end{equation} \] The squared parenthesis in the numerator increases, or alternatively remains unchanged if the new term \(b_{k+1}x_{k+1}=0.\) \(R^{2}\) for this new model is equal to or greater than \(R^{2}\) for the model with fewer variables. If we add more variables, \(R^{2}\) risks increasing even though the new regression model we thereby create cannot explain variations in the explained variable more than the previous regression model. This does not mean that \(R^{2}\) is a worthless measure but we must be aware of these characteristics when we use it. Another common measure is adjusted \(R^{2}\), which is denoted \(R_{	ext{adj}}^{2}\) or \( ar{R^{2}}\): \[  egin{equation}  ar{R^{2}}=1-\left(1-R^{2}ight) rac{n-1}{n-k-1} \end{equation} \] Calculations with \(y\) and \(\hat{y}\)Table 23.11: \(i\) \(y_{i}\) \(\hat{y}_{i}\) \(y_{i}-\hat{y}_{i}\) \(y_{i}- ar{y}\) \(\left(y_{i}-\hat{y}_{i}ight)^{2}\) \(\left(y_{i}- ar{y}ight)^{2}\) 1 3 3.2 \(-0.2\) \(-0.5\) 0.041 0.25 2 2 1.86 0.14 \(-1.5\) 0.018 2.25 3 5 4.59 0.41 1.5 0.164 2.25 4 4 4.34 \(-0.34\) 0.5 0.114 0.25 Mean 3.5 Sum 0.3378 5 where k is the number of explanatory variables and n is the number of observations. For the regression model \(y=a+bx+v\) we have one explanatory variable \(x\) with an associated coefficient, therefore \(k=1\). In the regression model \(y=a+bx+cz+v\) we have the two explanatory variables \(x\) and \(z\), therefore \(k=2\). Let us now estimate \(R^{2}\) and \( ar{R^{2}}\